Process

Our team used a structured discussion process during our technical meetings by taking turns to voice over their opinions. When disagreements about design choices arose, each member was given time to explain their point of view without interruption. Team members were encouraged to use respectful language and focus on data acquired from experiments rather than personal opinions. Active listening was expected, and responses were given after a short pause to ensure thoughtful replies. If discussion became difficult to resolve, the team lead mediates the discussion, while ensuring all viewpoints were considered before making a final decision.

Impact
 
This discussion process improved communication within the team by ensuring everyone had the opportunity to express their ideas and technical concerns. Because members focused on evidence and respectful dialogue, disagreements about circuit design or control strategies were less likely to become personal conflicts. The approach helped build trust and encouraged open discussion of alternative ideas, which improved problem solving and design decisions. As a result, the team maintained a friendly environment where differing viewpoints contributed to better solutions and more effective progress on the mouse project.
